{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1166"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.25,0.24,0.09,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108166"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4493"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37259"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108166"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 57-year-old man is admitted with a mild episode of cholecystitis. He has been unwell for 12 hours with right upper quadrant pain. On examination he looks well and his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse rate 90/min and temperature 37.2C. His BMI is 31. There is mild tenderness in the right upper quadrant. An ultrasound confirms the presence of gallstones, with mild thickening of the gallbladder wall and a small amount of pericholecystic fluid. A cholecystectomy is planned for the day after admission. As part of his management, consideration must be given to the need for appropriate antibiotic usage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No antibiotics required throughout","Single dose antibiotic at the start of the cholecystectomy","Antibiotics to start on admission and continued until the completion of surgery","Antibiotics to start on admission and to continue until the time of discharge","Antibiotics to start on admission and to continue for five days after surgery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has uncomplicated acute cholecystitis. Whilst some clinicians may chose not to use antibiotics in cases of mild cholecystitis in otherwise well patients with no co-morbidities, the standard practice is to administer antibiotics to all patients with acute cholecystitis. This will involve \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics to start on admission and continued until the completion of surgery\u003C/strong\u003E. Empiric antibiotics (according to local hospital guidelines) should be given on admission. This will be followed by a laparoscopic cholecystectomy during the current admission, with the patient ready to be discharged home the next day. The presence of co-morbidities such as frailty, diabetes or an immunocompromised state mandates antibiotic usage. Whilst this patient does not have one of these co-morbidities, he is obese and his procedure is known to be delayed until the following day so it would be prudent to ensure he is given antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe data on antibiotic usage for cholecystectomy are limited and the 2018 Tokyo guidelines recommend using antibiotics prior to and at the time of operative intervention for all patients with uncomplicated acute cholecystitis. There is no good evidence that routine use of antibiotics postoperatively is associated with any improvement in outcomes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, following the cholecystectomy, antibiotics can be ceased (and do not need to be continued until the time of discharge, nor for five days after surgery). Some degree of antibiotic prophylaxis is required, and a single dose at the start of cholecystectomy is not sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antibiotic usage is essential for complicated acute cholecystitis or where the patient has significant co-morbidities."],"references":["Pisano M, Allievi N, Gurusamy K, Borzellino G, Cimbanassi S, Boerna D, et al. 2020 World Society of Emergency Surgery updated guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute calculus cholecystitis. World Journal of Emergency Surgery. 2020;15(1). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33153472/","Gomi H, Solomkin JS, Schlossberg D, et al. Tokyo guidelines 2018: antimicrobial therapy for acute cholangitis and cholecystitis. J Hepatobiliary Pancreat Sci. 2018;25(1):3-16.  Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/jhbp.518","Gallaher JR, Charles A. Acute Cholecystitis A Review. JAMA 2022; 327:965-75. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2789654"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T13:59:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-07T14:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1166"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108166"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":fals